sections.english:
Once the Blessed One was staying in Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the Squirrels' Feeding Ground. Then Princess Cundī, surrounded by five hundred chariots and five hundred maidens, approached the Blessed One. Having approached, she paid homage to the Blessed One and sat down to one side. Seated to one side, Princess Cundī said to the Blessed One: "Venerable sir, our brother, Prince Cunda, says this: 'Whoever, be it a woman or a man, has gone for refuge to the Buddha, to the Dhamma, and to the Saṅgha; who abstains from the destruction of life, from taking what is not given, from misconduct in sensual pleasures, from false speech, and from consuming intoxicants that lead to heedlessness – such a one, upon the breakup of the body, after death, reappears in a good destination, never in a bad destination.'" "Venerable sir, I ask the Blessed One: 'Having confidence in what kind of teacher, venerable sir, does one, upon the breakup of the body, after death, reappear in a good destination, never in a bad destination? Having confidence in what kind of Dhamma does one, upon the breakup of the body, after death, reappear in a good destination, never in a bad destination? Having confidence in what kind of Saṅgha does one, upon the breakup of the body, after death, reappear in a good destination, never in a bad destination? Having fully completed what kind of virtues does one, upon the breakup of the body, after death, reappear in a good destination, never in a bad destination?'"

"Cundī, among all beings – whether footless, two-footed, four-footed, or many-footed; with form or formless; percipient, non-percipient, or neither percipient nor non-percipient – the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Self-Awakened One, is declared to be the foremost. Those, Cundī, who have confidence in the Buddha, they have confidence in the foremost. For those who have confidence in the foremost, the foremost result ensues.

"Cundī, among all conditioned phenomena, the Noble Eightfold Path is declared to be the foremost. Those, Cundī, who have confidence in the Noble Eightfold Path, they have confidence in the foremost. For those who have confidence in the foremost, the foremost result ensues.

"Cundī, among all phenomena, whether conditioned or unconditioned, dispassion is declared to be the foremost. That is to say, the subduing of intoxication, the removal of thirst, the uprooting of attachment, the cutting off of the cycle of existence, the destruction of craving, dispassion, cessation, Nibbāna. Those, Cundī, who have confidence in this foremost phenomenon of dispassion, they have confidence in the foremost. For those who have confidence in the foremost, the foremost result ensues.

"Cundī, among all assemblies or groups, the Saṅgha of the Tathāgata's disciples is declared to be the foremost. That is to say, the four pairs of noble persons, the eight individual noble persons – this Saṅgha of the Blessed One's disciples is worthy of offerings, worthy of hospitality, worthy of gifts, worthy of reverential salutation, and is the unsurpassable field of merit for the world. Those, Cundī, who have confidence in the Saṅgha, they have confidence in the foremost. For those who have confidence in the foremost, the foremost result ensues.

"Cundī, among all virtues, the virtues dear to the noble ones are declared to be the foremost. That is to say, they are unbroken, unblemished, unspotted, untarnished, freeing, praised by the wise, untainted by craving, and conducive to concentration. Those, Cundī, who fully complete these virtues dear to the noble ones, they are the foremost in their completion. For those who are foremost in their completion, the foremost result ensues."

For those with confidence in the foremost, who know the foremost Dhamma;
For those with confidence in the foremost Buddha, the unsurpassed worthy of offerings;
For those with confidence in the foremost Dhamma, which is dispassion, peace, and happiness;
For those with confidence in the foremost Saṅgha, the unsurpassable field of merit;
By giving gifts in the foremost, foremost merit proliferates;
Foremost life, beauty, fame, renown, happiness, and strength.
The wise giver of the foremost, established in the foremost Dhamma,
Whether born as a deity or a human, rejoices, having attained the foremost.

Monks, there are these five benefits in giving. Which five? One becomes dear and pleasing to many people; virtuous and noble individuals associate with one; a good reputation concerning one spreads far and wide; one does not fall away from the duties proper to a householder; and upon the dissolution of the body, after death, one reappears in a good destination, in a heavenly world. Indeed, monks, these are the five benefits in giving.

One who gives becomes dear, following the Dhamma of the virtuous;
The virtuous always associate with them, as do the self-restrained practitioners of the holy life.
They teach them the Dhamma, which removes all suffering;
Having understood that Dhamma here, they attain final Nibbāna, taintless.

Monks, there are these five advantages for a faithful householder's son. What are these five? Those good people who exist in the world, monks, show compassion primarily for the faithful, not so much for the faithless. They primarily approach the faithful, not so much the faithless. They primarily accept offerings from the faithful, not so much from the faithless. They primarily teach the Dhamma to the faithful, not so much to the faithless. The faithful, with the breaking up of the body, after death, are reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world. These, monks, are the five advantages for a faithful householder's son.

Just as, monks, a great banyan tree at a crossroads in fertile ground is a refuge for birds from all directions, even so, monks, a faithful householder's son becomes a refuge for many people: for monks, nuns, male lay followers, and female lay followers.

A great tree, adorned with branches, leaves, and fruits, with a thick trunk;
Rooted and abundant with fruit, it is a dwelling place for birds.

In that delightful abode, birds seek refuge in it;
Those seeking shade go for its shade, and those seeking fruit eat its fruit.

Even so, a person endowed with virtue, a faithful individual,
Living humbly, without arrogance, gentle, amiable, and soft-spoken.

Those who are rid of passion, rid of hatred, rid of delusion, taint-free;
The fields of merit in the world, they frequent such a person.

They teach him the Dhamma, which dispels all suffering;
Having understood that Dhamma here, he attains final Nibbāna, taint-free.
